response:
Okay, let's break down this request. The user wants to configure a custom Time to Live (TTL) attribute for data expiration using Terraform. This typically involves setting a TTL on a data source or resource that stores data. Since the request is quite general, I'll implement this for an AWS S3 bucket using the `aws_s3_bucket` resource, setting a lifecycle rule to expire objects based on a specified number of days.  I will also add a default TTL of 30 days. This is a common use case for data expiration. This example will focus on setting an expiration lifecycle rule on an S3 bucket, which would cause S3 to delete objects after a configured TTL.

```hcl
resource "aws_s3_bucket" "example" {
  bucket = "unique-bucket-name" # Replace with a unique bucket name
  acl    = "private"

  lifecycle_rule {
    id      = "expire-old-versions"
    enabled = true

    expiration {
      days = 30 # Default TTL of 30 days
    }
  }

  tags = {
    Name        = "My Example S3 Bucket"
    Environment = "Dev"
  }
}
```

